To expand a bit on what I said,

Worldbuilding is something to avoid, because you can’t tell beforehand what you’ll want to include in the story. You might have two ideas you’d like to include in a story sometime that are mutually exclusive, but if you include one in the worldbuilding, you can find yourself later on wanting to include the other idea instead. But, because you included the first one in the lore instead and latched it into the lore of the world, you can’t exactly remove it now that it’s stuck in.

>Traveller

1/2

I think there was some attempt to write some stuff about interspecies relationships for the Traveller RPG some years back.

I can't recall the name of the article or where I found it but the writers tried to be semi-plausible and true to the spirit of the source material that the creators of the RPG drew on--which was 40s-60s skiffy, with big influences especially from Poul Andersen's Ensign Flandry stories, Gordon Dickson's Dorsai stories, Jack Vance's "Planet of Adventure," Asimov's Foundation trilogy, Laumer's blackly humorous "Retief" short stories, Tubb's "Dumarest of Terra" adventure stories, H. Beam Piper's novel "Space Viking," and others. They were notable in our context for mainly lacked big-tittied green-skilled alien whammen, much less any of the YIFF YIFF YIFF YIFF stuff.

If you want to read a sample, Space Viking has reverted to the public domain: http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/20728 It's very bleak, borderline grimdark science fiction from what we are all told was a vastly more optimistic, innocent time. Atomic rocket ships shaped like an artillery shell with fins, with control panels like a World War II bomber, covered in vernier dials and gauges abound, as do streetwise hardcases in spacesuits with WWII-style stamped sheetmetal submachineguns slung over their shoulders and, of course, Hard Men Making Hard Choices.

2/2

Anyway. Traveller is a pen-and-paper RPG set in the far future, in a galaxy inhabited by multiple intelligent starfaring species. Only humans, the Vargr (anthro space wolves, genetically engineered thousands of years ago from a mixture of wolf and human genes), the Aslan (anthro space lion-ish, sorta), and the K'Kree (vegetarian vaguely bovine centaur people not very similar, either in psychology or appearance, to any earthly species). There are also the Droyne (anthro lizards, but VERY alien in psychology) and the Hivers (intelligent sea anemone-ish or maybe starfish are closer, psychologically extremely alien).

And someone wrote this up back in 1993 and put it on the Interwebs:

http://www.shoestring-graphics.com/traveller/AlienSex/

The short version is: it doesn't happen very much. It is in fact extremely rare to the point of being almost unheard-of, though in-universe there are cheap romance novels about it, generally about human women and Vargr or Aslan. Very few male humans find female Vargr attractive--they aren't cute awoos with big titties--and Aslan culture regards non-Aslan as inferior and the idea of sex with non-Aslan as shameful and disgusting. Also, human and Aslan genitalia are different enough that most forms of sexual intimacy are difficult, frustrating, even painful, for both, even if both partners are willing. And K'Kree are by human standards fugly, and hate all the other intelligent races. So, no YIFF YIFF YIFF here, sorry.

For an alternate viewpoint, but also rather dark, James Tiptree's "And I Awoke to Find me on the Cold Hill's Side," about a far future in which there is a despised human subculture of alien-fuckers:

http://www.lightspeedmagazine.com/fiction/and-i-awoke-and-found-me-here-on-the-cold-hills-side/

Anonymous Tue 11 Dec 2018 19:28:57 No.19982930 Report
Quoted By: >>19989252
>>19979574
>Being like 40 years old now, much of the Original Traveller Universe is full of inconsistencies and tech\science issues that, back in the 80's weren't so bad, now kind of blur the line between canon and fanon.

You're not wrong. But remember that Traveller isn't supposed to be realistic extrapolation into the future. It's a retro dieselpunk Galactic Empire, with spaceships that have vernier dials on their control panels and atomic rocket engines straight out of Heinlein's "The Green Hills of Earth," with melancholy overtones of Gibbon. It's 1951's space-opera future, with adventuring groups of hard-eyed gunslingers with death-rays on their hips, hired by the Imperial Spice Company to find out who's behind the labor riots on the planet that produces most of Deneb Sector's cinnamon--and the culprit is as likely to be a hostile interstellar government as it is to be a rival company in the spice business. Traveller was deliberately and consciously retro even when it was created.

And yes, if you want to incorporate /hmofa/ you'll need to make some changes. Maybe a place to start would be--well, see image attached. Both sexes of Vargr look like this--they are in fact almost identical in appearance when clothed and their sexuality is mainly mediated by pheromones. You could, I suppose, make female Vargr a bit more attractive, with big anime eyes and titties. Then again, then they're Florence Ambrose.

Goodness knows the artists went back and forth on this stuff. GDW Traveller Aslan were tall muscular humanoids with vaguely cat-like ears, long hair, and claws. Mongoose Traveller Aslan are full-on cat people, and the females are catgirls and even have titties. They still have a society that regards interspecies sex as taboo and weird genitalia that aren't compatible with human genitalia, though. I suppose you could change this.

Anonymous Tue 11 Dec 2018 23:35:11 No.19987248 Report
Quoted By: >>19987558
>>19987049
How similar would they be, anatomically, to IRL horses?

Real world horses, for example, can move terrifyingly fast for something that weighs half a ton or more, and can run very long distances. They have what the anatomy textbooks call a "reservoir spleen" that holds one third of their red blood cells in reserve, already oxygenated, ready to dump into the bloodstream when stimulated by the fight-or-flight response. In most mammals the spleen is only a blood filter and you can live without it. A horse can live without its spleen but they're basically crippled and can do little more than walk back and forth in the paddock.

Florence Ambrose is indeed best wolf.

But I was thinking in terms of the setting. In-setting, Vargr aren't just humans with animal heads and a lot of body hair. They're alien. They aren't stupid but they don't see the world as humans do, don't think as human's do. This gives the storyteller opportunities to describe humanity through alien eyes.

For one example, they're pack hunters. Dunbar's Number is much lower for them. They form packs of no more than a few dozen individuals that live as an extended family, led by the smartest or at least most charismatic among them, and they are very loyal to the pack alpha and to the greater good of the pack. They can't wrap their heads around the idea of loyalty to, for example, a Galactic Emperor hundreds of light-years away. If they can't see the alpha in person every day and talk to him, he stops existing to them. Human society looks, to them, brainwashed. Humans seem insane and monomaniacal in their devotion to a government, to a leader--to any ideal other than "what's good for my family and my shipmates right now." Vargr will happily fight and kill other Vargr to protect their own packs. Vargr inhabit many worlds and there is a region of the galaxy where they predominate, but it has no central government, just thousands of constantly shifting and warring alliances. The very idea of a central government is utterly alien to them.

Many individual Vargr work in human space as mercenaries or technicians or laborers, and can happily accept the humans around them as a sort of surrogate pack--but humanity in the aggregate, in the abstract, terrifies them. When no humans are around they look over their shoulders and make little jokes about humanity being some kind of hivemind. The punchline to most Vargr jokes about humans is "and then Joe the Vargr landed his ship this primitive planet human world out beyond the fringe, and went into the nearest town, and the first human he saw said 'Hi Joe!'"

Vargr aren't stupid. They just have really cut-throat (literally) politics. And according to the source material, their genetically-uplifted-to-sentient ancestors were placed on a garden world far from other sentient races, perhaps as an experiment, by extremely advanced aliens who appear to have left some time later. The Vargr learned to make fire, then to smelt metal, all on their own. They developed civilization--thousands of civilizations. And a few thousand years back, they figured out atomic power and faster-than-light travel.

Unfortunately, when they met the neighbors, it was usually as pirates and raiders. It's what Vargr do best. They do it to each other as enthusiastically as they do it to other species.

They have a long and bloody history with the Vilani--the descendants of Earth humans transplanted to many other worlds in that region of space by the same aliens who created the Vargr and put them a few tens of light years away, though the Vilani were given high tech and faster than light travel rather than creating them on their own.

Apparently there are Vargr who live on Vilani worlds and have somewhat assimilated their culture. If you read the material there are actually numerous Vargr ethnic groups--including one that a nation among the Vilani genetically engineered further and bred to be slaves for humans. And, as you might expect, different Vargr ethnic groups hate one another and make war against one another with great enthusiasm. But then, so do human nations in the settled galaxy of the far future.
